<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920310-0152</DOCNO><DOCID>920310-0152.</DOCID><HL>   BIC Considers Moving Business</HL><DATE>03/10/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   BIC F.SBI</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS AND SERVICES (HOU)DURABLE HOUSEWARE PRODUCTS (HPD)CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS (HPR)</IN><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)EUROPE (EU)FRANCE (FR)NORTH AMERICA (NME)SOUTH CAROLINA (SC)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   MILFORD, Conn. -- BIC Corp. said it is considering movingits marker manufacturing businesses outside the state ofConnecticut.   BIC's president, Raymond F. Winter, said, &quot;Connecticut'shigh operating costs continue to be a major concern,&quot;including high taxes, energy expenses and insurance costs.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;If a decision is made to move, it will most probably beto South Carolina,&quot; he added.   BIC has about 1,000 employees in Milford, where it hasbeen since the early 1960s. The company also hasmanufacturing facilities in Florida, South Carolina, Mexicoand Guatemala. Its 1991 sales were $369 million.</TEXT></DOC>